52a9ae02-af57-4c7a-a33e-41e1ae6a952d.03ce92f5-992f-425a-8498-a5ccffd64731.description=This flow is used to Create Problems. Inputs host - The URL of the ServiceNow instance. Format\: scheme\://domain Example\: https\://dev10000.service-now.com authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. Default value\: basic Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma. Example\: basic | basic,digest username - The ServiceNow username used to perform the request. password - The ServiceNow password used to perform the request. apiVersion - The API version with which the request will be sent. The call will be made using the latest API version when this input is left empty. Example\: v1 requestBody - The string to include in the body of the request, in the format accepted by ServiceNow. In case more Problem fields need to be addressed, they can be provided in the "requestBody" input. When a custom body is provided, the values provided in the inputs named "problem" will be ignored unless their reference is used in the new body. Example\: {'short_description'\:'Example description','severity'\:'1','assigned_to'\:'46c1293aa9fe1981000dc753e75ebeee','state'\:'4'} problemShortDescription - The short description of the Problem to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, the short description of the created Problem will be empty. problemDescription - The description of the Problem to be created, in the form of a string. If this input is left empty, description of the created Problem will be empty. problemNumber - The number of the Problem to be created. Should contain the "PRB" prefix followed by 7 or more digits. If this input is left empty, ServiceNow will automatically assign a number. Example\: PRB0100001 problemConfigurationItem - The system ID of the Configuration Item. (CMDB CI) Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 problemPriority - The Priority of the Problem, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 problemChangeRequested - The system ID of the Change that was requested. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 problemKnowledge - The boolean value of the "Knowledge" field. Valid values\: true, false problemKnownError - The boolean value of the "Known Error" field. Valid values\: true, false problemCloseNotes - The Close Notes in the form of a string. problemWorkaround - The Workaround in the form of a string. problemWorkNotes - The Work Notes in the form of a string. problemOpenedBy - The system ID of the entity that requested submitted the Problem. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 problemState - The State of the Problem, in the form of a positive integer. Each integer represents an Problem State as follows\: 1\=Open, 2\=Known Error, 3\=Pending Change, 4\=Closed/Resolved. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4 problemAssignmentGroup - The system ID of the Assignment Group. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 problemAssignedTo - The system ID of the entity to which the Problem should be assigned to. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 preemptiveAuth - If this field is "true", authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is "false" a request with no authentication info will be made and if the server responds with 401 and a header such as WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm", only then will the authentication info be sent. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site. proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used. proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value. trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it. Default value\: false Valid values\: true, false x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker (Man-In-The-Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option. Default value\: strict Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties. If the protocol (specified by the URL) is not HTTPS or if trustAllRoots is "true" this input is ignored. Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS) trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied. Default value\: changeit connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds Examples\: 10, 20 socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of 0 represents an infinite timeout. Default value\: 0 Format\: an integer representing seconds useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes). Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route. Default value\: 2 connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections in total. Default value\: 20 headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:". Format\: According to HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). Examples\: Accept\:text/plain responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS. Default value\: ISO-8859-1 followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects. Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false requestCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP request body. If contentType is empty, the requestCharacterSet will use the default value. If contentType will include charset (ex.\: "application/json; charset\=UTF-8"), the requestCharacterSet value will overwrite the charset value from contentType input. This should not be provided for method\=GET, HEAD, TRACE Default value\: ISO-8859-1 Results\: returnResult - This will contain the response entity. In case of an error this output will contain the error message. document - This will contain the response body. exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception. statusCode - The HTTP status code. Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request) Examples\: 200, 404 responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline. Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616). systemId - The system ID of the created Problem. Responses success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (headers, proxy, queryParams, url). Notes\: 1. The reference of the "problem" inputs should be removed from inside the "requestBody" input when they are deleted. 2. When more Problem fields are required, than the ones exposed, you can add them as inputs and insert their reference in the Json found in the "requestBody" input. 3. In order to authenticate using an OAuth token\: 3.1. The headers input should contain the following header\: Authorization\:Bearer 3.2. The username and password inputs should remain empty. 52a9ae02-af57-4c7a-a33e-41e1ae6a952d.a2381020-1dca-4842-91fa-41132bf93980.description=
Checks if a number or word is equal to another number or word. Word comparison is case-sensitive in alphabetical order.

Inputs\:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.

Returns\:
value1 \=\= value2

Responses\:
success - The boolean operation was evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.
52a9ae02-af57-4c7a-a33e-41e1ae6a952d.c008c380-34b4-42ac-8c27-4bfebc2786a3.prompt=Notification option\: 52a9ae02-af57-4c7a-a33e-41e1ae6a952d.description=
Use this template when you are creating a new flow. You should remove the Success or Failure step.

Responses\:
    success - the flow completed successfully.
    failure - the flow completed unsuccessfully.
52a9ae02-af57-4c7a-a33e-41e1ae6a952d.fc9b51f2-01d4-44a3-8336-1270fc48d4b0.description=
This flow sends, stores or displays a notification message according to your notification type selection. You can use this flow to select how to be notified about the outcome of other flows. 

Inputs\:
    notifyData -  The content of the notification message.
    notifyMethod - The notification type. This value is not case sensitive.
Valid values\: Write to File, Email, Display or None
    subject - A summary of the notification content. 
    destination - The destination of the notification. You must specify a value for this input if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’ or ‘Write to File’.
Valid values\: An email address or a file name
    notificationServer - The email server used to send the notification email message. If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    from - The email address of the sender of the notification email message.  If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    serverPort - The notification service’s server port. This field’s value is used when the "notifyMethod" is ‘Email’, but it is optional.
Default value\: 25
    htmlEmail - The value should be true if the email is in rich text/HTML format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.
Default value\: true

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
    To schedule a flow that uses this flow, you need to supply all the required fields for the used notification method. For example, if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘File’, the "destination" input must also be specified.

Examples\:
    This is a valid input example for storing a notification message to a file\:
      notifyData\: notificationContent
      notifyMethod\: Write to File
      subject\: notificationSubject
      destination\: C\:\Program File\notification.txt
